fy” pupils in the Third Reich. But significant discontinuities existed as well, especially regarding the teachers' professional self-understanding and attitudes toward the state-sanctioned teachers' union. The mixture of continuities and discontinuities helped to stabilize the early GDR as it faced its first major crisis in the uprising of June 17, 1953. This uniquely comparative work sheds new light on an essential story as it reconceptualizes the traditional periodization of postwar German and European history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunism and educationzGermany (East). 0aEducation and statezGermany (East)xHistory. 0aEducation and statezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducationzGermany (East)xHistory. 0aEducationzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational socialism and education. 0aTeacherszGermany (East)xHistory. 0aTeacherszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674059740?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674059740423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674059740/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles